Owińska

In January 2014 I took a trip to the village of Owińska with a friend of mine. The main objective was to see and take pictures of an abandoned mental hospital which witnessed the killing of about one thousand patients during World War II (apparently, Owińska was also notorious for its German concentration camp and an SS school named after Adolf Hitler). Before we got to the building, we came across what turned out to be a palace built in the early 19th century for Otton von Treskow, the owner of the village (currently abandoned as well), and the Cisterian Monastery which now houses a special school for blind children.

To our disappointment, when we reached the grounds of the hospital, it turned out that the entire area had been privatized and was inaccessible to anyone without the owner's permission. Thus, the only shots of the structure were taken from beyond the wall since we never got a chance to go inside.
